SEMDL Help Topic: reference remove

Usage:
- `ssd remove <selector[,selector...]> <file>`
- `ssd remove <selector[,selector...]> --cascade <file>`
- `ssd remove <selector[,selector...]> --dry-run <file>`
- `ssd remove <selector[,selector...]> --stdout <file>`
- `ssd remove <selector[,selector...]> --out <output.ssd> [--dry-run] <file>`
- `ssd remove type:<kind> --allow-multi [--stdout|--dry-run|--out <output.ssd> [--dry-run]] <file>`
- `ssd remove type:<kind> --allow-multi --cascade [--stdout|--dry-run|--out <output.ssd> [--dry-run]] <file>`

Purpose:
- Remove one Sidekick metadata field or one structural target set when the selector resolves safely.
- Structural removals fail on inbound references unless `--cascade` removes dependent targets in the same step.
- Explicit comma-separated structural selector lists resolve each `id:`, `path:`, or `type:` atom and remove the union target set.
- `--stdout` and `--out` return the post-remove canonical inline `.ssd` without mutating the source files.
- `type:<kind>` list atoms still require `--allow-multi` when they expand to multiple targets.
- `type:<kind> --allow-multi --cascade` expands the same cascade edge list across the matched root set and the same union rules apply inside selector lists.

Related help:
- `ssd help grammar`
- `ssd help recipes wrong-layer`

Sample:
- `ssd remove meta:A1.embedding docs/examples/minimal.ssd`
- `ssd remove id:ALT1B --stdout docs/examples/minimal.ssd`
- `ssd remove id:ALT1A,id:ALT1B docs/examples/minimal.ssd`
- `ssd remove id:H1 --cascade docs/examples/minimal.ssd`
- `ssd remove type:hypothesis --allow-multi --cascade --out docs/examples/remove-multi-cascade-output.ssd --dry-run docs/examples/remove-multi-cascade-source.ssd`
